  "text": "Our results are consistent with risk-sensitive TD (RSTD) learning. In RSTD learning, nonlinearity is associated with the learning process rather than the evaluation of outcomes, with positive and negative prediction errors having asymmetric affects on changes in predictions (Fig. 3c) . Applying a nonlinear transformation to prediction errors (as in RSTD learning) rather than to outcomes (as in the utility model) maintains the simplicity of recursive learning, as in traditional TD learning [CITATION_1] . This form of learning predicts a precise relationship between amount of outcome variance and deviations from the risk-neutral mean value, as a function of the differences between Ϫ and ϩ for each subject. Because in the present experiment only one stimulus was associated with variable outcomes, we could not compare the effects of different degrees of variance, leaving this for future work. Another yet-unanswered question is whether the asymmetry is fixed, or adapts to the amount of risk in the task (or to other characteristics such as volatility or amount of training). For instance, [CITATION_2] identify neural substrates correlating with signals that can be used to learn explicitly about the risk associated with different outcomes.",
